13.1Example

1   Introduction

This document describes the RPC interface towards the SDP.

The messages of this interface are RPC requests over TCP/IP. The protocol is based on Sun RPC, see ref [1], using TCP/IP.

The operations labeled as requests in this document is sent towards the SDP and those labeled responses are sent as response from the SDP.

The SDP will parse and syntax check the requests before the needed service (execute command, get, update, delete, or create data) is requested.

[Missing image client-sdp_interface.gif]

Figure 1   Client-SDP Interface

2   Syntax Notation

This section describes the notation used in the protocol specification.

2.1   Block

The order of the blocks and the order of the parameters in a block is fixed. The blocks may not be combined arbitrarily. Possible combinations are described in this document. If the Client sends an illegal combination the SDP will answer with an error code. See Error Codes in chapter 5.

2.2   Type definitions

In the request- and response tables the parameters are defined. The columns to the right defines the type and the different types are defined in the chapters below.

2.2.1   M â mandatory

The parameter is always present.

2.2.2   C â conditional and mandatory

Example: C means that the parameter only is present depending on other parameter or block.

2.2.3   O â optional

The parameter is optional.

When one O, meaning optional, is specified for two or more adjacent rows together, then this means that if one of the parameters is present, then the other(s), for which the same O is specified, has/have to be present also.

In the example below, if either of param2, param3 or param4 are present then all of the three parameters must be present.

2.2.10   Several layers of logic

If there are several layers (columns) of logic then the logic is applied from left to right. Any parameters that are grouped within a layer are considered as one entity in the next layer. A grouped entity is considered present if at least one parameter within the group is present, and is absent otherwise. The rules received from all layers must be fulfilled.

3.2   Update

The Update requests adds, subtracts, changes, and/or sets entities and/or entity values in the SDP.

3.2.1   Update operation syntax

The following blocks are single blocks and can not be combined with other blocks:

  • AccountFaF
  • SubscriberFaF
  • MovePromotion
  • PeriodicAccountManagement
  • MidCycleRerating (PC:14893)

If the CommunicationID block is present then the Charging block is mandatory. No other blocks are allowed in such a request.

If the Charging block is present then at least one of the following two Blocks must also be present:

  • ServiceClass
  • TemporaryServiceClass

The currency parameter must be included in the request if either of the following parameters is present in the request:

  • amount (in AccountBalance Block)
  • dedicated_amount (in DedicatedAccount Block, currency is only required if dedicated_unit_type is set to 1 (Money))
  • prom_refill_amount (in ActivePromotion Block)
  • prom_progress_amount (in ActivePromotion Block)
  • account_prepaid_empty_limit (in SubscriberAdjustment Block)

Parameter temp_blocked in Block SubscriberAdjustment can not be combined with any other change of data, not within the block or in combination with other blocks.

The value parameter in the Accumulator Block depends on the action value in the same block. The value parameter must be absent if action is RESET, and present if action has any other value.

The EnhancedServiceFeeActivation block will be present in the response if the PC is active and the SubscriberSegmentation block is present in the request.

The currency parameter in the ERROR response will be included if the cost parameter is included.

To update sub-DAs (date and/or amount) within a Composite DA the parameters: action_ded_acc_amount, dedicated_amount and dedicated_unit_type are mandatory.

When updating Block=Attributes the response includes Block=Attributes with all attribute values if there are any attributes with values. Attributes without values are never returned. An attribute does not have a value if the attribute is defined as a set, but neither the subscriber has a personal value defined nor does the set have any global values defined.

In an update request, the Offer block can be used to create a product or an offer with its attributes set. To change (add, clear or delete) an attribute for an existing offer or product use the Attributes block.

When the backdate_to_datetime or backdate_to_start_of_billcycle_instance parameter is present in the header section the DedicatedAccount, Offer, UsageCounterAndThreshold, and Attributes blocks become single blocks and can not be combined with other blocks. The Offer and Attributes blocks may be combined with each other but no other blocks.

BUC10B_A

To update predefined offer values (block predefinedOfferValues) for an offer, an attribute- or tree parameter sequence or both must be included in the request.

BUC10B_A end

3.3   Get

The Get requests retrieves information about entities in the SDP.

3.3.1   Get operation syntax

The AllPromotions block is single block and can not be combined with other blocks.

SubscriberFaF and AccountFaF blocks can only be combined with each other.

The Get request operation must contain at least one requested Block.

If the Charging block is present, then the Subscriber block must also be present in the request.

If DedicatedAccount block is present but empty then all dedicated accounts are requested.

If Accumulator block is present but empty then all accumulators are requested.

The currency parameter in the ERROR response will be included if the cost parameter is included.

The flags_after and flags_before parameters are only present in the Success Response if a Subscriber block is present in the request.

If the UsageCounterAndThreshold block is present, then information about all usage counters (personal and common) and usage thresholds (personal and defined) + values for the requested subscriber is requested. The response will only include usage counters with connected usage thresholds where usage counter is not 0 or a personal usage threshold is provisioned. This means that if a subscriber has no personal usage thresholds provisioned and no usage counter is stepped, the response will be an empty UsageCounterAndThreshold block.

BUC283A_B

The GlobalParameterValues block will only return personal global parameter values.

BUC283A_B end

This RPC message creates entities in the SDP.

The following block combinations are permitted:

  • Subscriber, Promotion and PeriodicAccountManagement
  • SubscriberFaF and Charging

Otherwise one single block must be present in the request.

The currency parameter in the successful response will be included if the cost or account_prepaid_empty_limit parameter is included.

The currency parameter in the ERROR response will be included if the cost parameter is included.

3.5   Delete

The Delete requests removes entities in the SDP.

3.5.1   Delete operation syntax

Allowed block combinations:

  • SubscriberFaF and Charging

Otherwise one single block must be present in the request.

The currency parameter in the successful response and ERROR response will be included if the cost parameter is included.

For Block = Offer, the currency parameter in the response will only be output if there are dedicated accounts connected to deleted offers.

For Block = UsageCounterAndThreshold, the parameters currency and number_of_decimals in the response, will only be output if a usage threshold has usage_value_type = 2 (money)

Note:  
If Periodic Account Management data exists for a subscriber and DELETE is performed with the Subscriber block, the PeriodicAccountManagement block will also be included in a successful response.

4   Elements

4.1   account_balance

Range: (-999 999 999 999) - 999 999 999 999

This parameter contains the account balance of a subscriber

4.2   account_group_id

Range: 0 â 2147483647

0 (zero): Reserved for reset of account_group_id

1 â 2147483647: account_group_id

This parameter contains the account group identity for the account.

4.3   account_home_region

Range: 0 â 999

0 (zero): No account home region is set.

This parameter contains the home region for the account.

4.4   account_prepaid_empty_limit

Range: (-999 999 999 999) â 999 999 999 999, <EMPTY>

This parameter gives the lowest allowed credit limit on the account.

âThe <EMPTY> value is only allowed in an UPDATE request, and will remove the existing Account Prepaid Empty Limit.

4.5   account_reservation (PC:12399)

Range: 0 - 999 999 999 999

This parameter contains the number of monetary units that are reserved on the main account.

4.6   account_time_zone (PC:07061)

Range: Text string

This parameter contains a string of 1-256 characters, where the time zone is based on the Olson TZ Database (part of the JavaTM framework), which contains close to 600 different time zone text strings, e.g. Etc/GMT+5, EST, EST5EDT and America/Whitehorse.

It is important that these time zones are specified exactly as the Olson TZ Database, as they will be used directly by the JavaTM framework (see the JavaDoc or tz database WIKI for more information).

Specifying "Default" will result in SDP System time zone.

4.7   accumulator

Range: 1 â 2147483647

This parameter indicates the identity of the usage accumulator affected by the operation.

4.8   accumulator_sequence

Sequence parameter with usage accumulator ids.

Sequence syntax: lowIDâhighID

ID range: 1 â 2147483647

Example: accumulator_sequence=212-215

4.9   accumulator_value

Range: (-2147483648) â 2147483647

This parameter states the value for a usage accumulator. This parameter could hold a negative value.

4.10   action

Range: ADD, SUBTRACT, SET, RESET

For an AccountBalance block this parameter specifies whether the following amount should be added to or subtracted from the main account balance. Using PC:05163 it is also possible to use the SET action to specify that the amount should be set.

For an Accumulator Block this parameter specifies whether the following value should be added to or subtracted from the current value. It is also possible to set the accumulator to the specified value, or to reset the accumulator to 0.

For an AcctMgmtCounter block this parameter specifies whether the total_counter_value and period_counter_value should be added to or subtracted from the current value of total counter and period counter. It is also possible to set the total counter and period counter to the respective total_counter_value and period_counter_value.

For a UsageCounterAndThreshold block this parameter specifies whether the following value should be added, subtracted or set to the usage counter.

4.11   action_attribute

Range: ADD, DEL, CLEAR, SET

This parameter contains the requested action for an attribute.

- With action ADD, a value is added to the set (for attributes storing a set of values).

- With action DEL, a value is deleted from the set (for attributes storing a set of values).

- With action CLEAR, all entries are deleted from the set (for attributes storing a set of values) or removes the value for a single value attribute.

- With action SET, a value of a single value attribute is stored (previous value, if existing, will be overwritten).

The following actions are allowed for an attribute storing a set of values: ADD, DELETE, CLEAR

The following actions are allowed for an attribute storing a single value: SET, CLEAR

4.12   action_ded_acc_amount

Range: SET, ADD, SUBTRACT, EXPIRE

If the dedicated accounts balance is updated, then this parameter indicates if the values is to be set, added or subtracted with the dedicated_amount.

The value EXPIRE is used to expire a dedicated account as soon as possible.

The value EXPIRE may not be combined with a dedicated_product_id.

4.13   action_faf_number_list

Range: ADD, SET, DEL

The Family and Friends (FaF) number list consist of specific subscriber numbers, or number series. The FaF number list is associated either with a subscriber or an account.

- With the ADD action, a new entry or entries are added in theFaF number list.

- With the SET action, the k_indicator value can be changed for an existing entry in the FaF number list.

- With the DEL action and one or more entries, the entries are deleted from the FaF number list. The DEL action without any entry, will clear all entries in the FaF number list.

4.14   action_global_parameter (BUC283A_B)

Range: ADD, DEL, CLEAR, SET

This parameter contains the requested action for a global parameter.

- With action ADD, a value is added to the set (for global parameters storing a set of values).

- With action DEL, a value is deleted from the set (for global parameters storing a set of values).

- With action CLEAR, all entries are deleted from the set (for global parameters storing a set of values) or removes the value for a single value attribute.

- With action SET, a value of a single value global parameter is stored (previous value, if existing, will be overwritten).

The following actions are allowed for a global parameter storing a set of values: ADD, DEL, CLEAR

The following actions are allowed for a global parameter storing a single value: SET, CLEAR

4.15   action_mid_cycle_rerating (PC:14893)

Range: MARK, UNMARK, CANCEL

This parameter contains the mid cycle rerating action to perform.

- Action MARK means that the subscriber is marked for rerating.

- Action UNMARK means that the subscriber is unmarked for rerating and the account snapshot is loaded.

- Action CANCEL means that the mid cycle rerating is canceled and the subscriber is unmarked for rerating without loading the account snapshot.

4.16   action_offer

Range: EXPIRE

This parameter is used to indicate which action to take on the offer.

4.17   action_prom_progression

Range: ADD, SUBTRACT

This parameter indicates if the provided promotion plan progression amounts are to be added to or subtracted from the accumulators.

4.18   action_prom_refill

Range: ADD, SUBTRACT, ADD_AMOUNT_RESET_COUNTER (PC)

If a promotional refill is going to be applied, then this parameter tells if the promotional refill is going to be added or subtracted. ADD_AMOUNT_RESET_COUNTER is a PC. ADD_AMOUNT_RESET_COUNTER will add the amount in the request and reset the counter at the same time

4.19   action_refill_barring

Range: CLEAR, INCREASE

This parameter tells if the refill fraud counter of a subscriber shall be increased or cleared.

4.20   action_tree_parameter

Range: ADD, DEL, CLEAR, SET

This parameter contains the requested action for a tree parameter.

- With action ADD, a value is added to the set (for tree parameters storing a set of values).

- With action DEL, a value is deleted from the set (for tree parameters storing a set of values).

- With action CLEAR, all entries are deleted from the set (for tree parameters storing a set of values) or removes the value for a single value attribute.

- With action SET, a value of a single value tree parameter is stored (previous value, if existing, will be overwritten).

The following actions are allowed for a tree parameter storing a set of values: ADD, DEL, CLEAR

The following actions are allowed for a tree parameter storing a single value: SET, CLEAR

4.21   activation_date

Range: YYYY-MM-DD

This parameter contains the activation date of an account.

4.22   activation_map (PC)

Range: 1 - 2147483647

A 32 bit value with those bits set that corresponds to personal service offerings updated on the account level due to this request. If any of the requested service offering bits were already set/unset on the account, those will be reflected as unset. Therefore, this value indicates what service offerings updates were actually made on the account.

4.23   active_days (PC)

4.24   active_flag

1 - Active discount.

0 - Planned discount.

4.25   aggregated_balance (PC)

4.26   aggregated_reservation (PC:12399)

This parameter contains the total sum of the monetary units reserved on the main account and on all dedicated accounts defined as real money.

4.27   allow_crop_of_sub_dedicated_account

Range: 1

If this parameter is set to one, it is allowed to set the dates on the composite dedicated account to values inside the dates of the sub dedicated accounts. The sub dedicated accounts outside the dates of the composite dedicated account will be deleted. Sub dedicated accounts with only one date outside will have its date changed but the balance is left unchanged.

If this parameter is not set, the request will be rejected if the dates on the composite dedicated account is set to values inside the dates of the sub dedicated accounts.

4.57   community_id_list_new

Range: 1 â 9999999, <EMPTY>

A comma separated list

The community_id_list contains 0 up to 3 community_id:s. Each community id is separated only by a comma â no space is used in between the id:s.

In an Update Community List request, all existing community identities will be replaced with the new values.

In an Update Community List request with community_id_list_new = ââ (empty string), the action means clear (all community identities are cleared).

The community ids in the list must be âleft adjustedâ, meaning that no value are allowed to follow an empty string in the list. Example: community_id_list_new=<4,,9> is not allowed.

4.115   faf_number

This is an entry in the Family and Friends (FaF) number list. An entry either consists of a specific subscriber number, or of a number series.

4.268   time_restriction_start_time (PC:07061)

Range: 0-86399

The start time for the restriction is represented as the number of seconds since midnight. Calculated using; HH * 3600 + MM * 60 +SS, where HH is between 00 - 23, MM is between 00 - 59 and SS is between 00 - 59.

The start time is 'inclusive', often denoted as >=, such that '07:00:00' would include the start second it is specifying, 07:00:00, 0700:01, 07:00:02....

A restriction can only be based on the same 24-hour period, this means that in order to set a restriction between 19:00:00 and 07.00:00, two restrictions are required, one for 19:00:00 until 23:59:59 and another one for 00:00:00 until 06:59:59.

4.269   time_restriction_end_time (PC:07061)

Range: 0-86399

The end time for the restriction is represented as the number of seconds since midnight. Calculated using; HH * 3600 + MM * 60 +SS, where HH is between 00 - 23, MM is between 00 - 59 and SS is between 00 - 59.

The end time is 'inclusive', often denoted as <=, such that '12:04:00' would include 12:03:58,12:03:59,12:04:00 up until it switches over to 12:04:01. It includes the end second it is specifying.

A restriction can only be based on the same 24-hour period, this means that in order to set a restriction between 19:00:00 and 07:00:00, two restrictions are required, one for 19:00:00 until 23:59:59 and another one for 00:00:00 until 06:59:59.

6   State Behavior

7   Compatibility Mechanisms

A client must use the 'version' element of the request header to indicate protocol version so that a server can provide different answers depending on protocol version.

8   Transfer Mechanism

This protocol uses RPC as a transfer mechanism, see ref [1] for specifics. Messages are encoded as a linked list containing variable length character strings. Each node in the linked list consists of a character string with a name/value pair which corresponds to the "name = value" format described in the protocol message and a pointer to the next node in the list. When the next node pointer contains a NULL value it signifies the last entry in the message. Although the message specifications use "<" and ">" to delimit values, these characters are not included in the actual string.

Some parameters can be used without values. In that case the construct âparameter_name = â is used in both request and response messages, thus no value is specified but the parameter name and the equal sign are provided.

9   XDR Specification

This is the XDR specification for the SDP-RPC interface.

typedef string msgtype<>; /* Variant length char array */
typedef struct msgnode *GSAmsgPtr; /* Pointer to link in message */

struct msgnode
{ /* Node in list */
  msgtype msg_item;
  GSAmsgPtr next;
};

program GSA_GW_RPC_PROG
{ /* Definition of RPC routine */
  version GSA_GW_RPC_VERS_ORIG
  {
    GSAmsgPtr SEND_GSA_MSG(GSAmsgPtr) = 1;
  } = 1;
} = 0x20000200;

11.17   Changes from RPC 4.0 to RPC 4.1

11.17.1   Update Operation

  • Rules for permitted block combinations are changed.
  • Block Charging is now Optional
  • Block SubscriberSegmentation has an additional OR column to indecate that at least one parameter is required in the request.
  • Block DedicatedAccount now has service_class as Mandatory parameter and an additional OR column within the dedicated_account_id sequence. Also dedicated-amount has been changed from optional to mandatory. Changes are in the request. Parameter dedicated_champion_identifer included in response.
  • Block Accumulator now has service_class as Mandatory parameter and an additional OR column within the accumulator sequence in the request.
  • Block AcctMgmtCounter now has two additional OR columns within the counter_id sequence. The AcctMgmtCounter block is now Optional. Changes are in the request.
  • not_allowed_reason is optional in the error response.
  • cost is Optional in the error response.
  • currency is Conditional in the error response.
  • Error response now includes codes 51 and 52.
  • duplicating_CDR_node added in Update request.
  • Parameter temp_blocked in Block SubscriberAdjustment can not be combined with any other change of data, not within the block or in combination with other blocks.

11.17.2   Get Operation

  • Rule that Subscriber block must be included if the Charging block is included added.
  • Rule that at least one Block must be present in the Request is added.
  • The Charging block is now Optional
  • The AcctMgmtCounter block is now Optional
  • The requested_info_flag is now Optional in the request.
  • In the SubscriberFaF block the parameters faf_change_unbar_date and max_allowed_numbers are now Optional in the request.
  • In the SubscriberFaF block the charged_faf_not_allowed_for_sc parameter has been added as an optional parameter in the request.
  • Marked master_subordinate_flag, service_class, language, flags_before, and flags_after as mandatory in successful response.
  • sc_change_unbar_date is now optional in the response.
  • not_allowed_reason is Optional in the error response.
  • cost is Optional in the error response.
  • currency is Conditional in the error response.
  • Error response now includes codes 51 and 52

11.17.3   Create Operation

  • The Charging block is now Optional
  • selected_option in the Charging block is now Optional in the request.
  • not_allowed_reason is Optional in the error response.
  • max_allowed_numbers is Optional in the error response.
  • cost is Optional in the error response.
  • currency is Conditional in the error response.

11.17.4   Delete Operation

  • The Charging block is now Optional
  • cost_service is Optional in the successful response.
  • not_allowed_reason is Optional in the error response.
  • max_allowed_numbers is Optional in the error response.
  • cost is Optional in the error response.
  • currency is Conditional in the error response.
  • Error response now includes codes 51 and 52.
  • Add block SubscriberFaF (faf_change_unbar_date and max_allowed_numbers) to Delete successful responses.
